## Why `levelSize` Is Important

At the start of every level, the queue contains only the nodes of that level.

Example:


queue = [2, 3]
levelSize = 2


While processing `2` and `3`, we add their children `5` and `4`.

But those children belong to the next level.

Because `levelSize` is fixed at `2`, the for loop only processes `2` and `3`.

Then the next while loop iteration processes `5` and `4`.

This keeps levels separated correctly.

---

## Why `i == levelSize - 1` Works

At every level, nodes are processed from left to right.

Example:

```text
Level 1:
2, 3
```

Indexes:

```text
i = 0 -> node 2
i = 1 -> node 3
```

The last index is:

```text
levelSize - 1 = 1
```

So node `3` is the last node in that level.

That is the node visible from the right side.

---

## Complexity

### Time Complexity

```text
O(n)
```

Every node is visited once.

### Space Complexity

```text
O(n)
```

In the worst case, the queue can store many nodes from one level.

For a complete binary tree, the last level can contain around `n / 2` nodes.




